In the first scenario:

1. Create an EmployeeDTO model class with the necessary fields:

```java
    public class EmployeeDTO {
    private int id;
    private String name;
    private String empType;
    // Getters and setters 
}
```
2. Implement a custom **deserializer** that maps the JSON values to the desired representation:
```java
public class EmployeeTypeDeserializer extends JsonDeserializer&lt;String&gt; {
    @Override
    public String deserialize(JsonParser jsonParser, DeserializationContext deserializationContext) throws IOException {
        String empType = jsonParser.getValueAsString();
        if (&quot;SENIOR&quot;.equals(empType)) {
            return &quot;C-9&quot;;
        } else if (&quot;JUNIOR&quot;.equals(empType)) {
            return &quot;C-10&quot;;
        }
        return empType;
    }
}
```
3. Annotate the empType property in the EmployeeDTO class with **@JsonDeserialize** to specify the usage of the custom deserializer:

```java
@JsonDeserialize(using = EmployeeTypeDeserializer.class)
private String empType;
```

Alternatively, you can achieve the desired mapping by using a setter method:

```java
